  <example xml:id="rational-end-behavior-example-5">
    <title>End Behavior</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Find the end behavior of <m>r(x)=\dfrac{4x^3-9x^2+4x-6}{5x^{8}-17x^7+3x-4}</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>r(x) \to 0</m> as <m>x \to \pm\infty</m>.
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Since the degree of the numerator is 3 and the degree of the denominator is 8, we see that the degree of the denominator is larger than the degree of the numerator. This shows the existence of a horizontal asymptote <m>y=0</m>.
      </p>
      <p> 
        Therefore, <m>r(x) \to 0</m> as <m>x \to \pm\infty</m>.
      </p>
      <figure>
        <caption>As the the values of <m>x</m> get closer to <m>\pm\infty</m>, the graph of <m>r(x)</m> gets closer to but never reaches the <m>x</m>-axis.</caption>
        <image source="chapter-6/rational-end_behavior_example_5.png" decorative="yes" width="50%"/>
      </figure>
      </solution>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="rational-end-behavior-example-6">
    <title>End Behavior</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Find the end behavior of <m>r(x)=\dfrac{9x^{12}+3x^5-2x^2}{12x^{12}-4x^9+3x^7+x}</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>r(x) \to \dfrac{3}{4}</m> as <m>x \to \pm\infty</m>.
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Since the degree of the numerator is 12 and the degree of the denominator is 12, we see that the degrees of the numerator and denominator are equal. Therefore, there is a horizontal asymptote <m>y=\dfrac{a_n}{b_m}=\dfrac{9}{12}=\dfrac{3}{4}</m>.
        </p>
      <p>  
        Therefore, <m>r(x) \to \dfrac{3}{4}</m> as <m>x \to \pm\infty</m>.
      </p>
      <figure>
        <caption>As the the values of <m>x</m> get closer to <m>\pm\infty</m>, the graph of <m>r(x)</m> gets closer to but never reaches the line <m>y=\dfrac{3}{4}</m>.</caption>
        <image source="chapter-6/rational-end_behavior_example_6.png" decorative="yes" width="50%"/>
      </figure>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="rational-end-behavior-example-7">
    <title>End Behavior</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Find the end behavior of <m>r(x)=\dfrac{x^3+4x^2-4x-16}{x^2-2x-3}</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
       <m>r(x) \to x+6</m> as <m>x \to \pm\infty</m>, .
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Since the degree of the numerator is 3 and the degree of the denominator is 2, the degree of the numerator is one more than the denominator. Therefore, there is an oblique asymptote found using polynomial long division.
      </p>
      <figure>
        <caption>Polynomial Long Division of <m>x^3+4x^2-4x-16</m> by <m>x^2-2x-3</m> has a quotient of <m>x+6</m>.</caption>
        <image source="chapter-6/rational-end_behavior_example_7_division.png" decorative="yes" width="50%"/>
      </figure>
      <p>
        This gives us the oblique asymptote <m>y=x+6</m>. Therefore, <m>r(x) \to x+6</m> as <m>x \to \pm\infty</m>.
      </p>
      <figure>
        <caption>As the the values of <m>x</m> get closer to <m>\pm\infty</m>, the graph of <m>r(x)</m> gets closer to but never reaches the line <m>y=4x + 5</m>.</caption>
        <image source="chapter-6/rational-end_behavior_example_7.png" decorative="yes" width="50%"/>
      </figure>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="end-behavior-example-8">
    <title>End Behavior</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Find the end behavior of <m>r(x)=\dfrac{x^4+8x^3+12x^2-32x-64}{x^2-2x-3}</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>r(x) \to x^2+10x+35</m> as <m>x \to \pm\infty</m>.
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Since the degree of the numerator is 4 and the degree of the denominator is 2, the degree of the numerator is larger than the degree of the denominator by 2 or more. Therefore, there is a nonlinear asymptote found using polynomial long division.
      </p>
      <figure>
        <caption>Polynomial Long Division of <m>x^4+8x^3+12x^2-32x-64</m> by <m>x^2-2x-3</m> has a quotient of <m>x^2+10x+35</m>.</caption>
        <image source="chapter-6/rational-end_behavior_example_8_division.png" decorative="yes" width="50%"/>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Therefore, the nonlinear asymptote is <m>y=x^2+10x+35</m>. Therefore, <m>r(x) \to x^2+10x+35</m> as <m>x \to \pm\infty</m>.
      </p>
      <figure>
        <caption>As the the values of <m>x</m> get closer to <m>\pm\infty</m>, the graph of <m>r(x)</m> gets closer to but never reaches the parabola <m>y=x^2+10x+35</m>.</caption>
        <image source="chapter-6/rational-end_behavior_example_8.png" decorative="yes" width="50%"/>
      </figure>
    </solution>
  </example>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-crossing-asymptotes">
  <title>Crossing Horizontal/Oblique/Nonlinear Asymptotes?</title>
  <p>
    From our graphs, we notice that the graph of a rational function <m>r(x)</m> may cross its horizontal, oblique, or nonlinear asymptote. 
    These are important points to plot when sketching the graph of <m>r(x)</m> since we may need to cross these asymptotes to make sure our end behavior is correct. 
    </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-crossing-asymptotes">
      <title>How To Determine if a Rational Function Crosses Its Horizontal, Oblique, or Nonlinear Asymptote</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>r(x)=\dfrac{p(x)}{q(x)}</m> be a rational function with a horizontal, oblique, or nonlinear asymptote.
        </p>
        <p>
          To find where <m>r(x)</m> crosses its horizontal, oblique, or nonlinear asymptote, 
          <ol>
            <li>Set <m>r(x)</m> equal to the asymptote and solve for <m>x</m>.</li>
            <li>For each solution, evaluate <m>r(x)</m> to find the corresponding <m>y</m>-coordinate.</li>
            <li>Plot each point <m>(x,y)</m> on the graph of <m>r(x)</m>.</li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </lemma>
<example>
    <title>Crossing an Asymptote</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Find where <m>r(x)=\dfrac{x^2+2x}{x^2+1}</m> crosses its horizontal asymptote <m>y=1</m> .</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>The graph of <m>r(x)</m> crosses its horizontal asymptote at <m>\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)</m>.</p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>To find where <m>r(x)</m> crosses its horizontal asymptote, we set <m>r(x)=1</m> and solve for <m>x</m>.
        <md>
          <mrow>r(x) \amp=1\\ </mrow>
          <mrow>\dfrac{x^2+2x}{x^2+1} \amp=1\\ </mrow>
          <mrow>x^2+2x \amp=x^2+1\\ </mrow>
          <mrow>2x \amp=1\\ </mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp=\dfrac{1}{2}\\ </mrow>
        </md>
        Since the asymptote is horizontal, the <m>y</m>-coordinate is always <m>1</m>.
        Therefore, there is only one point where the graph crosses the horizontal asymptote: <me>\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)</me></p>
    <figure xml:id="crossing-horizontal-asymptote">
      <caption>The graph of <m>r(x)</m> crosses the line <m>y=1</m> at the point <m>\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)</m>.</caption>
      <image source="chapter-6/crossing_horizontal_asymptote.png" decorative="yes" width="50%"/>
    </figure>
      </solution>
      </example>
<example>
    <title>Crossing an Asymptote</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Find where <m>r(x)=\dfrac{x^3-3x^2+4}{x^2-2x+2}</m> crosses its oblique asymptote <m>y=x-1</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>The graph of <m>r(x)</m> crosses its oblique asymptote at <m>\left(\frac{3}{2},\frac{1}{2}\right)</m>.</p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>To find where <m>r(x)</m> crosses its oblique asymptote, we set <m>r(x)=x-1</m> and solve for <m>x</m>.
        <md>
          <mrow>r(x) \amp=x-1\\ </mrow>
          <mrow>\dfrac{x^3-3x^2+4}{x^2-2x+2} \amp=x-1\\ </mrow>
          <mrow>x^3-3x^2+4 \amp=(x-1)(x^2-2x+2)\\ </mrow>
          <mrow>x^3-3x^2+4 \amp=x^3-3x^2+4x-2\\ </mrow>
          <mrow>-4x+6 \amp=0\\ </mrow>
          <mrow>-4x \amp=-6\\ </mrow>
          <mrow>x\amp=\dfrac{-6}{-4}\\ </mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp=\dfrac{3}{2}\\ </mrow>
        </md>
        Evaluating <m>r\left(\frac{3}{2}\right)</m>
        <md>
          <mrow>r\left(\dfrac{3}{2}\right) \amp=\dfrac{\left(\dfrac{3}{2}\right)^3-3\left(\dfrac{3}{2}\right)^2+4}{\left(\dfrac{3}{2}\right)^2-2\left(\dfrac{3}{2}\right)+2}\\ </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp=\dfrac{\dfrac{27}{8}-\dfrac{27}{4}+4  }{\dfrac{9}{4}-3+2}\\ </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp=\dfrac{5/8}{5/4} \\</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp=\dfrac{5}{8} \cdot \dfrac{4}{5} \\</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp=\dfrac{1}{2} </mrow>
        </md>
        Therefore, there is only one point where the graph crosses the oblique asymptote: <me>\left(\dfrac{3}{2},\frac{1}{2}\right)</me></p>
    <figure xml:id="crossing-oblique-asymptote">
      <caption>The graph of <m>r(x)</m> crosses the line <m>y=x-1</m> at the point <m>\left(\frac{3}{2},\frac{1}{2}\right)</m>.</caption>
      <image source="chapter-6/crossing_oblique_asymptote.png" decorative="yes" width="50%"/>
    </figure>
      </solution>
   
      </example>
</subsection>

</section>